        "quote": "How the youthful Harlot's curse",
        "analysis": "The \"youthful Harlot\" is a figure of destroyed innocence. \"Youthful\" emphasises her age — she is young, possibly a teenager, driven to prostitution by poverty and the absence of any social safety net. Blake does not condemn her; she is a victim, not a villain. Her \"curse\" works on multiple levels: it is a verbal curse (an expression of rage and despair), a physical curse (the venereal disease she passes to her clients and their families), and a symbolic curse (the moral sickness that afflicts all of London). The word \"Harlot\" was more clinical than offensive in Blake's time, but it still marks her social status — she is defined entirely by her exploitation. Blake places her at the poem's climax because she embodies every failure of the system.",
