        "explanation": "Both \"London\" and \"Ozymandias\" explore the abuse of political power, but from very different perspectives. Blake's poem is set in the present, showing power as an active, ongoing force that crushes the lives of ordinary people — the \"charter'd streets,\" the soldier's blood on Palace walls, and the institutional corruption of Church and state are all immediate realities. Shelley's \"Ozymandias,\" by contrast, shows power from the vantage point of the distant future, where even the most tyrannical ruler has been reduced to a shattered statue in the desert. Where Blake focuses on the suffering of the powerless, Shelley focuses on the hubris of the powerful and the inevitable decay of their authority. Together, the poems offer complementary critiques: Blake shows what tyranny does to people, while Shelley shows what time does to tyrants. Both poets were radicals who challenged the political establishment, and both use irony as their primary weapon — Blake through the word \"charter'd,\" Shelley through the gap between Ozymandias's boast and his ruined monument."
