        "analysis": "The mountain is personified as a living creature that rises up of its own will. \"Voluntary power instinct\" suggests the peak possesses an innate, deliberate force — it is not merely a geological feature but an active agent with intention. The verb \"Upreared\" gives the mountain animal-like qualities, as though it is rearing up like a horse or a predator. This personification transforms the natural landscape from a passive backdrop into a threatening, sentient presence. Wordsworth uses this to convey the Romantic idea that nature is not just scenery but a powerful, living force that can assert its authority over human beings. The boy's confident mastery of the boat and the lake is suddenly overturned by the mountain's assertion of its own power."
